  "doc_id": "41108",
  "text": "Our approach is not the first to capture program behavior in terms of callingcontext information. Ammons et al. [CITATION_1] show how to generate context-sensitive performance profiles efficiently, using hardware performance counters. Dynamic sandboxing, proposed by Inoue et al. [CITATION_2] , shows similarities with behavior compliance control. Like behavior compliance control, dynamic sandboxing relies on dedicated training runs to determine a set of legal behaviors. However, Inoue et al. only consider profiles at function granularity and validate them in two very limited scenarios; in particular, they do not provide a detailed, quantitative evaluation and do not consider a broader applicability of dynamic sandboxing beyond runtime monitoring.",
